\begin_layout Subsection
Formulas to compute monetary effects of carbon tax policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "appendix:formulas"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to compute the monetary impact of a carbon tax increase, we decompose current energy expenditures 
\begin_inset Formula $E(\tau)$
\end_inset

 as a product of current price 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and current quantities consumed 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(\tau)$
\end_inset

, each being a function of the excise tax 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 within which the carbon tax is comprised:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
The French carbon tax 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Contribution Climat Energie
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a component of existing taxes on energetic products: TICPE for transport and domestic fuels, TICGN for natural gas.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E\left( \tau \right) = P\left( \tau \right) Q\left(\tau\right)
\]
\end_inset

All variations in expenditures can then be expressed as: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{dE}{E}\left(\tau\right) = \frac{dP}{P}\left(\tau\right) + \frac{dQ}{Q}\left(\tau\right)
\]
\end_inset

from which we can write the effect of a price change on quantities consumed: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
Q\left(\tau '\right) = Q\left(\tau\right) \left(1 + e\frac{dP}{P}\left(\tau\right)\right)
\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $e = \frac{dQ}{dP} \cdot \frac{P}{Q}$
\end_inset

 is the price elasticity of the energetic good considered, that is here assumed constant. For all energies, the final price can itself be decomposed as: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
P\left(\tau\right) = \left(p+i\tau\right)\left(1+t\right)
\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the value added tax (VAT) rate that applies after excise taxes, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 the incidence of excise taxes on consumers assumed constant, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p + \left(i-1\right)\tau$
\end_inset

 the producer price as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and for a given value of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the producer price for a given value of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau = 0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When the carbon price changes so that the excise taxes varies from 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 to some level 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau'$
\end_inset

, we therefore have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{dP\left(\tau\right)}{P} = \frac{P\left(\tau '\right) - P\left(\tau\right)}{P\left(\tau\right)} = \frac{\left(p + i \tau '\right)\left(1+t\right) -  \left(p + i \tau\right)\left(1+t\right)}{\left(p + i \tau\right)\left(1+t\right)} = \frac{i\left(\tau' - \tau\right)}{p + i \tau}\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Thus, following a carbon price increase, one can express the associated increase in expenditures for each energy as: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E\left(\tau'\right) - E\left(\tau\right) = E\left(\tau\right)\left(1+e\right) \frac{dP}{P} = E\left(\tau\right)\left(1+e\right) \frac{i\left(\tau' - \tau\right)}{p + i \tau}
\]
\end_inset

We can replicate similar calculations to obtain the expected variations in tax revenue 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

. Starting from its expression — which is the sum of excise taxes and the VAT over this tax — we have: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
T\left(\tau\right) = Q\left(\tau\right) \left(\left(1+t\right) \tau + t \left(p + \left(i-1\right)\tau \right) \right)
\]
\end_inset

from which we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
T\left(\tau '\right) - T\left(\tau\right) = Q\left(\tau\right) \left( 1 + e \frac{i\left(\tau' - \tau\right)}{p + i \tau} \right) \left[ t \left(p + \left(i-1\right)\tau' \right) + \left(1+t\right) \tau' \right] - Q\left(\tau\right) \left[ t \left(p + \left(i-1\right)\tau \right) + \left(1+t\right) \tau \right]
\]
\end_inset

Following the literature, we assume price elasticities of 
\begin_inset Formula $-0.4$
\end_inset

 for transport fuels and 
\begin_inset Formula $-0.2$
\end_inset

 for housing energies. For the tax incidence on consumers, we assume a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.8$
\end_inset

. These values were used to compute aggregate variations in tax revenue and determine the level of lump sum transfer per adult that a budget neutral policy would finance. When asked to estimate the impact of the policy on their own purchasing power, respondents simply had to make an estimation over: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E\left(\tau'\right) - E\left(\tau\right) = E\left(\tau\right)\left(1+e\right) \frac{dP}{P}
\]
\end_inset

where for simplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $dP$
\end_inset

 was given for transport fuels, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dP}{P}$
\end_inset

 for housing energies. Thus, they were not required to make any specific assumption about existing taxes or tax incidence, but simply to estimate their consumption and price elasticity.
\end_layout

